ce:section.ce:para:
Since sensors are likely to interact with electron deficient analytes, binding ability of sensor 3 was investigated against various nitroaromatic explosives including 2,4,6-trinitrotoluene (TNT), 2,4,6-trinitrophenol (TNP), 2,4-dinitrotoluene (DNT), 4-nitrophenol (NP), 1,3-dinitrobenzene (DNB), and 2-nitroaniline (NA) through fluorescence and UV − Vis. spectroscopy. Fluorescence experiments were carried out in aqueous solution (100% H2O) by adding increasing concentration of nitroaromatic explosives. The emission spectrum of sensor 3 (40 μM) in aqueous solution (100% H2O) displayed weak emission band at λem of 447 nm (λexc = 275 nm). Upon the addition of increasing concentration of TNP (0–50 nM) to aqueous solution of sensor 3, an efficient enhancement in fluorescence emission of sensor 3 was observed as shown in Fig. 1
                        . Maximum enhancement in emission intensity of sensor 3 (50 folds) was observed at 50 nM of TNP with bathochromic shift of 17 nm (447–464 nm). Efficient fluorescence enhancement response with bathochromic shift was attributed to the electrostatic interaction between sensor 3 and TNP which suppressed the photoinduced electron transfer (PET) and induced rigidity in sensor, resulting in fluorescence emission enhancement. Fluorescence enhancement response was also accompanied by the appearance of dark blue color under UV radiations upon the addition of TNP (10 nM) to sensor 3 (500 nM) (Inset; Fig. 1A). For quantitative analysis of TNP, the fluorescence signals of sensor 3 were determined in the presence of varying concentrations of TNP (0–50 nM) and results are shown in the form of the Benesi–Hildebrand plot (Fig. 1B). Fluorescence intensity of sensor 3 increased linearly with the increasing TNP concentrations up to 50 nM. The association constant (Ka) of TNP complexation with sensor 3 was calculated from the linear regime of the Benesi–Hildebrand plot and was found to be 5.17 × 107 M−1. Large Ka value clearly indicates the strong association of sensor 3 with TNP [48]. Next, limit of detection (LOD) is also a significant feature to analyze sensitivity of a sensor [49]. The limit of detection (LOD) of sensor 3 for TNP was calculated as 0.5 nM from the formula; LOD = 3 σ/S. Herein, σ is the standard deviation and S is slope of the calibration curve. The detection limit and association constant values of sensor 3 for TNP is much better than already reported TNP sensors (comparison is provided in Table 2
                        ) that clearly demonstrates the excellent sensitivity of sensor 3 towards TNP.
